<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-085-230  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 085 230.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Jan 22 1990 v9 n2 p87(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Board suggests govt. concentrate on SES morale. (government;Senior Executive Service) (Merit Systems Protection Board)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Grimm, Vanessa Jo.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Merit Systems Protection BoardUnited States. Senior Executive ServiceManagementJob SatisfactionManpower PlanningWagesSurvey.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Why SES members leave the government. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Board Suggests Govt.andP;  Concentrate on SES MoraleandM;Low pay still is the biggest problem the government faces in retainingmembers of the Senior Executive Service (SES), but there is little agenciescan do to change that situation, the Merit Systems Protection Board reportedrecently.andM;Instead, agency officials should concentrate on those things they can controlsuch as job dissatisfaction and poor supervision by political appointees.andM;&quot;The compensation issues cannot be minimized,&quot; the board said in a recentreport on the SES.andM;Although SES salaries increased 70 percent during the last decade, the payrate still did not keep up with inflation, which rose 77 percent over thesame period.andM;The board surveyed former federal executives who had left the government inthe last five years.andP;  Fifty-seven percent of the former employees whoresponded to the survey said poor pay was one of the reasons they leftfederal service.andP;  Fewer than 13 percent said the government adequatelycompensates senior executives.andM;Seventy percent reported they did not believe the Civil Service Reform Acthad lived up to its promise of ensuring adequate pay to attract and retainSES employees.andM;The report, The Senior Executive Service: Views of Former Federal Executives,also showed a growing concern that the pay cap will continue.andM;&quot;While the possibility of a continued ceiling was a de facto reason for halfof the respondents who left the service in 1985 and 1986, it was a factor fornearly three-fourths of the former executives who retired or resigned in1988,&quot; the report said.andM;But because agencies have little leeway to set pay for SES members, officialsshould consider other ways to retain the executives, the report said.andM;The board said the Office of Personnel Management and the agencies shouldfocus on correcting the non-monetary problems cited in the survey such as jobdissatisfaction, poor supervision by appointed executives and ineffective useof SES employees' skills.andM;&quot;Agencies expend considerable effort in selecting the most qualifiedcandidates for career positions in the SES,&quot; the report said.andP;  &quot;They shouldexpend more effort in attempting to retain them.&quot;andM;The survey found 46 percent of the former executives left in part becausethey neither enjoyed their work nor found it rewarding and challenging.andO;Forty-two percent reported they did not fully use their talents in their SESjobs.andM;To combat both these problems, the board suggested agencies considerdeveloping distinct SES career paths with changing assignments andpossibilities for additional training.andM;Though other surveys have reported high marks for non-career executiveperformance, the board found 38 percent of the former SES employeesconsidered their appointed supervisors incompetent.andM;Agencies should ensure that appointees meet necessary qualifications andstandards set by OPM, the board said.andP;  Agencies also should develop intensiveappointee orientations and provide necessary specialized training, the reportsaid.andO;</TEXT></DOC>